<subSubSection id="C3786525FFDCFFA4FF28F9F868612840" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDD36AEFFDCFFA4FF28F9F868612840" blockId="32.[151,1436,1457,2022]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDCFFA4FF28F9F86A572928" bold="true" box="[199,321,1601,1626]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
General body color brown to dark brown. Pronotum without maculae or pruinosity on anterior lobe. Forewings of brachypterous form leaving most of tergites and connexives VI–VII exposed; forewing dark brown with lighter veins, and a basal elongated white macula starting from humeral angle and ending adjacent to posterior margin of pronotum; at apex another white macula, small and oval, very close to the posterior margin of wing (
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDCFFA4FA81F9146BA22998" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[283,1284,308,1583]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[279,1308,303,1587]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 19. Dorsal view, (A) Paravelia platensis (brachypterous), (B) P. spinifera, (C) P. williamsi, (D) ventral view of P. williamsi (arrow indicates the projections on sternite VII of male)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285800/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDCFFA4FF78F96B6BA22998" box="[151,180,1746,1770]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Male abdominal sternites V–VII medially prominent and slightly flattened; male sternite VII with posterior margin slightly extended medially, with two lobes surrounding a central concavity. Paramere with many elongated setae on inner and outer surface, and subtruncate apex (
<figureCitation id="13592A2BFFDCFFA4FCEBF8A0684E2840" box="[772,856,1817,1842]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[203,1383,582,1952]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[198,1389,577,1957]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Lateral view of genital capsule of male, (A) P. nieseri, (B) P. platensis, paramere in posterior view, (C) P. recens, (D) P. rotundanotata, (E) P. spinifera, (F) P. splendoris, (G) P. williamsi." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285801/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAA2489FFDCFFA4FCD7F8A3684E2840" box="[824,856,1818,1842]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3786525FFDCFFA4FF28F8846BC028EC" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDD36AEFFDCFFA4FF28F8846BC028EC" blockId="32.[151,1436,1457,2022]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="B916EABCFFDCFFA4FF28F8846A5A2824" bold="true" box="[199,332,1853,1878]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Discussion.</emphasis>
Known from the brachypterous and macropterous forms, and previously recorded from 
<collectingCountry id="F375763EFFDCFFA4FAC3F8846E8D2824" box="[1324,1435,1853,1878]" name="Argentina" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F375763EFFDCFFA4FF29F8DB6A3C2808" box="[198,298,1890,1914]" name="Uruguay" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
. Herein the species is recorded for the first time from 
<collectingCountry id="F375763EFFDCFFA4FC6BF8D868DD2808" box="[900,971,1889,1914]" name="Brazil" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, based on material collected in São Paulo State.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
